<font color="#FF0000">TO BETTY, RED CROSS WARRIOR </font><br>
<tt>Tue Oct 28 13:19:34 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Betty,<br>
Welcome back, your contributions are honrable.<br><br>
You wrote;<br><br>
ôI have to reread after the gut has been purged and try to address what the other person is really saying. I don't know if that is what discomforts you about my style of writing. ô<br><br>
I think you suffer from the same analytical watchfulness we all do. It maybe part of the distrust we inherited over the years that are connected to our experiences after the war. We seem to have suffered more from the after effects of our service then from our actual combat or in-country experiences. <br>
In Vietnam, we had the support and understanding of others who found themselves in the same surroundings, with the same desires, needs, understanding and concerns we all had. Afterwards the same military and services agencies that brought us together to serve became responsible for separating  our common bonds and just as quickly as it had brought us together it separated us from that unity and trust we all shared and cast us back into a world that had changed and which was no longer the world we once knew or loved.<br>
Instead of honor we received disgrace, instead of respect we were bombarded with hatred, but as the song goes we were never promised a rose garden and the funny thing is, we never really wanted one. <br><br>
I volunteered for duty, I knew I was going to war, in the corps I knew I would find danger not safety, hardship not ease, service not privilege and I like you served with honor, proud of what was accomplished, but came home to a different world.<br><br>
What I meant when I said about being pinned down all these years, is that the war we fought in Nam was not the type of war we had been trained for and that what we accomplished against the odds we faced has never truly been acknowledged by our government. <br>
We fought a conventional war without front lines, against an ever-evasive enemy that hit and ran and was very much like a phantom, or a vision of the night. When we did make contact and engaged the enemy, the battles we faced were fierce and dreadful, destructive and very much like running at a very rapid speed up against a solid wall.<br>
That was the type of war I fought and often when we were out in the open, crossing open rice paddy fields the enemy, usually hard corps Communist trained North Vietnamese regular soldiers would spring their ambush. They always opened up with all they could muster and so we would lay out in the open paddies as bullets flew overhead or struck the top of the small rice paddy dike we were hard pressed up against.<br>
We would remain there sometimes hours while we waited for other Marines to out flank the enemy or for artillery to drop heavy their ordinance upon the enemy, sometimes the enemy opened up right on top of us so that we could not call in artillery, naval gun fire, jets or gunships, and so there we would be pinned down for hours not knowing what we would do or what others were doing to get us out. <br>
Sometimes when the firing grew too intense and it appeared that the enemy might be getting ready to charge us and we couldnĺt move as you mention above to look up over the dike because the incoming rounds were so intense we would just place our weapons on top of the dike and without looking, open up shooting in the general direction the enemy was firing at us from. We called it spray and pray. <br>
I guess thatĺs what I mean by us still being  pinned down behind rice paddy dikes all these years. <br>
Often we have had to spray and pray as the politicians blamed us for loosing the war, as the social do gooders blamed us for the death of South Vietnamese civilians, as the protestors proclaimed that the war we fought was worthless. And so for the most part we remained silent. We have remained silent and stuck behind the rice paddy dikes of distorted history.<br><br>
We said to ourselves, why share with others what they donĺt understand. That is why I believe we are now, coming to an age of awareness where we are beginning to realize there is a very real need to leave the truth of our shared experiences to others. I believe our side of the story has never really ever been told. We have read of the battles, of the troubles VN veterans encountered there and upon our return stateside, but the true human interest stories, the coming of age and the sacrifices and the willingness we shared in accomplishing what we could with the resources we had and what support we had among ourselves, that has never really been told. That side of the Vietnam story has not been adequately told.<br><br>
Our fellow countrymen allowed others to place the guilt of Americaĺs shame upon our shoulders and so for the most part we laid silent behind rice paddy dikes waiting for the assault against our combat and military participation in South East Asia to cease. <br>
We have been pinned down all this years as the protestors, college professors, professional shrinks, journalist and others have explained their side of the conflict, and have recorded as historical facts what we know in our hearts was not right. The exploration of the Vietnam war without the political, ideological or liberal view has never been conducted. The human sacrifice and pride we felt for our service has never been recognized.<br><br>
All this time, however the closure we need has been lying there within us and among us and as we begin to stand up and to arise out of the muddy rice paddy fields of the injustice we have suffered under, we are finding out that we are not alone. We are also taking the time to reach back and pull up the others, those that have suffered the most, those who have been wounded in their hearts, minds and spirits. Those who have suffered physically as well and we are all beginning to stand upright and proud. I believe soon that voice will be heard loud and clear and will reveal what we did and what we accomplished was good and proper and we did it with honor and glory for our country, for what we believed in and it was not in vain.<br>
Here I went off on what I had not planned on writing about, but I guess it reveals from where I am coming from and where I plan to go. <br>
Welcome Betty, your presence will be an esset.<br><br>
In Peace and War,<br>
Cookie <br>

